---
import Page from '../../layouts/Page.astro';
---
<Page title="Kitchen Prep" description="How to give AI the context it needs to actually help you — the foundation of every great prompt.">
  <section class="page-hero container">
    <h1><span class="h1-emoji">🧑‍🍳</span> Kitchen Prep</h1>
    <p>The difference between a useful AI response and a generic one is almost always context. Here's what to give it and why.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="container prep-layout">
    <div class="prep-content">

      <section class="prep-section">
        <h2>Why context matters</h2>
        <p>AI doesn't know who you are, what you're working on, or what a good answer looks like for your situation. Without context, it defaults to the most average possible response — technically correct, practically useless.</p>
        <p>Think of it like briefing a new hire. The more relevant background you give, the better the work you get back.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="prep-section">
        <h2>The 5 context ingredients</h2>
        <div class="ingredients-grid">
          {[
            { icon: '🎯', label: 'Goal', desc: 'What are you actually trying to accomplish? Not just "write an email" but "write an email that gets a meeting with a cold prospect who\'s seen 50 pitches."' },
            { icon: '👥', label: 'Audience', desc: 'Who is this for? Their background, what they know, what they care about, and what would make them tune out.' },
            { icon: '📐', label: 'Format', desc: 'What does the output need to look like? Bullet points, paragraphs, a table, a specific word count, a specific tone?' },
            { icon: '🚧', label: 'Constraints', desc: 'What are the limits? What can\'t you do, what must you include, what would be a deal-breaker?' },
            { icon: '🗺️', label: 'Examples', desc: 'What does good look like? Even a rough example — "something like this but shorter" — dramatically improves results.' },
          ].map(item => (
            <div class="ingredient-card">
              <div class="ingredient-icon">{item.icon}</div>
              <div>
                <h3>{item.label}</h3>
                <p>{item.desc}</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="prep-section">
        <h2>Before vs. after</h2>
        <div class="compare-table">
          <div class="compare-row compare-header">
            <div>❌ Unprepared prompt</div>
            <div>✅ Well-prepped prompt</div>
          </div>
          {[
            { bad: 'Write me a bio.', good: 'Write a 3-sentence professional bio for a UX designer with 8 years of experience applying for a senior role at a fintech startup. Tone: confident but not arrogant. Audience: hiring manager.' },
            { bad: 'Summarize this article.', good: 'Summarize this article in 3 bullet points for a non-technical executive who needs to decide whether to fund further research. Focus on business implications, not methodology.' },
            { bad: 'Help me with my presentation.', good: 'I\'m presenting Q3 results to our board in 10 minutes. Sales missed target by 12%. Help me open with a frame that\'s honest about the miss but focuses the conversation on the recovery plan.' },
          ].map(row => (
            <div class="compare-row">
              <div class="compare-bad"><span class="compare-quote">"{row.bad}"</span></div>
              <div class="compare-good"><span class="compare-quote">"{row.good}"</span></div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="prep-section">
        <h2>The role frame shortcut</h2>
        <p>One of the fastest ways to add context is a role frame — telling the AI who it should be. This calibrates tone, vocabulary, and the type of advice it gives.</p>
        <div class="tip-block">
          <p><strong>Instead of:</strong> "Give me feedback on my code"</p>
          <p><strong>Try:</strong> "You are a senior engineer doing a code review. Your goal is to catch bugs and flag anything that won't scale. Be direct — don't soften criticism."</p>
        </div>
        <p>Browse ready-made role frames in <a href="/pantry/">The Pantry</a> or build your own in the <a href="/spice-rack/">Spice Rack</a>.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="prep-section">
        <h2>Follow-up prompts that fix almost anything</h2>
        <p>A single prompt is rarely the end of the conversation. These follow-ups work after any response to reshape, sharpen, or redirect:</p>
        <div class="followup-grid">
          {[
            { label: 'Too complex', prompt: '"Make this explanation simpler."' },
            { label: 'Wrong format', prompt: '"Turn this into a checklist."' },
            { label: 'Too abstract', prompt: '"Add real-world examples."' },
            { label: 'Too long', prompt: '"Cut this by half. Keep the substance."' },
            { label: 'Check assumptions', prompt: '"What assumptions are you making here?"' },
            { label: 'More depth', prompt: '"Go deeper on [specific part]."' },
            { label: 'Different angle', prompt: '"Now argue the other side."' },
            { label: 'Plain English', prompt: '"Explain this like I\'m smart but not a specialist."' },
          ].map(f => (
            <div class="followup-card">
              <span class="followup-label">{f.label}</span>
              <span class="followup-prompt">{f.prompt}</span>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
        <p>Think of your session as a conversation, not a single question. Iterative follow-ups consistently outperform trying to write one perfect prompt upfront.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="prep-section">
        <h2>Quick checklist</h2>
        <p>Before you hit send, ask yourself:</p>
        <ul class="checklist">
          <li>Does it know what I'm trying to accomplish?</li>
          <li>Does it know who this is for?</li>
          <li>Does it know what format I need?</li>
          <li>Have I told it what to avoid?</li>
          <li>Would a smart person reading only this prompt know what a good answer looks like?</li>
        </ul>
        <p>If yes to all five — you're ready to cook.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="prep-section" id="prompt-chaining">
        <h2>Prompt engineering is evolving</h2>
        <p class="section-kicker">From single mega-prompts to sequential chains — and why the shift produces dramatically better results</p>

        <div class="chain-callout">
          <span class="chain-stat">67%</span>
          <p>average improvement in output quality when switching from single complex prompts to 5-step chains — measured across writing, data parsing, and code generation workflows over 30 days.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>The problem with mega-prompts</h3>
        <p>When you pack everything into one giant prompt — context, instructions, format requirements, edge cases, examples — you're asking a single cook to prep, cook, plate, and run the whole restaurant at once. The model spreads thin.</p>
        <p>Single mega-prompts break down in predictable ways:</p>
        <ul class="chain-list">
          <li><strong>Hallucinations multiply.</strong> The more you ask at once, the more the model fills gaps with invented details to satisfy competing demands.</li>
          <li><strong>Focus dilutes.</strong> Competing instructions create ambiguity — the model optimizes for some requirements at the expense of others, and you can't predict which.</li>
          <li><strong>Context drift.</strong> In a long prompt, early constraints get de-prioritized as the model generates later parts of the response. The instruction you put first is often the one it "forgets."</li>
          <li><strong>No checkpoints.</strong> You can't catch errors mid-process. You get the whole output or start over — there's no place to course-correct.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>The solution: the 5-step chain</h3>
        <p>Prompt chaining breaks one complex workflow into ~5 sequential micro-prompts where <strong>Output A becomes Input B</strong>. Each prompt does exactly one thing, and does it well.</p>
        <div class="chain-steps">
          {[
            { n: '1', label: 'Define', desc: 'Establish scope, key angles, or raw material. Keep this prompt narrow.' },
            { n: '2', label: 'Structure', desc: 'Take the output of step 1 and build a skeleton — outline, schema, or plan.' },
            { n: '3', label: 'Generate', desc: 'Work through the structure one section at a time. Focus the model on a single chunk.' },
            { n: '4', label: 'Refine', desc: 'Pass the draft back in. Ask for a specific improvement — tighten, cut, or deepen. One lens only.' },
            { n: '5', label: 'Format', desc: 'Apply final structure, tone, or output requirements to the polished draft.' },
          ].map(s => (
            <div class="chain-step">
              <div class="step-num">{s.n}</div>
              <div>
                <strong>{s.label}</strong>
                <p>{s.desc}</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
        <p>Each step is focused, verifiable, and correctable before it feeds the next. You can swap, repeat, or branch any step without restarting from scratch.</p>

        <h3>Before vs. after: writing an article</h3>
        <div class="compare-table chain-compare">
          <div class="compare-row compare-header">
            <div>❌ Single mega-prompt</div>
            <div>✅ 3-step chain</div>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-row">
            <div class="compare-bad">
              <span class="compare-quote">"Research the topic of vector databases, write a 1,200-word technical blog post aimed at mid-level developers, include an intro, three sections with subheadings, a comparison table of the top 5 tools, real code examples in Python, and a conclusion with a CTA. Tone: authoritative but approachable. Don't be fluffy."</span>
              <p class="compare-note">Result: generic structure, shallow comparisons, the code doesn't match the tools in the table, the CTA is boilerplate. Total rewrite needed.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-good">
              <p class="chain-step-label">Step 1 — Research</p>
              <span class="compare-quote">"List the 5 most-used vector databases for production ML apps in 2025. For each: one-line summary, primary use case, and one concrete limitation."</span>
              <p class="chain-step-label">Step 2 — Outline</p>
              <span class="compare-quote">"Using this comparison [paste step 1 output]: write a 7-section outline for a 1,200-word technical blog post for mid-level developers. Each section gets a heading and 2-sentence description of what it covers."</span>
              <p class="chain-step-label">Step 3 — Draft section by section</p>
              <span class="compare-quote">"Write section 3 of this outline in full [paste section 3 description]. Tone: direct, no padding. Include one Python snippet showing a real insert operation."</span>
              <p class="compare-note">Result: each section is coherent, the code matches what was discussed, the comparison table is accurate. Minor edits only.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="chain-source">
          <p>Methodology and benchmarks via <a href="https://x.com/godofprompt/status/2021552838774780007" target="_blank" rel="noopener">@godofprompt</a> — 30-day structured testing across writing, parsing, and code generation workflows.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="prep-section" id="further-reading">
        <h2>📚 Further reading</h2>
        <p>Want to go deeper? These are the best technical pieces on context engineering, memory, cost, personas, and output reliability.</p>
        <div class="reading-list">
          {[
            {
              title: "Effective Context Engineering for AI Agents",
              source: "Machine Learning Mastery",
              tag: "Context Engineering",
              desc: "A developer's guide to structuring context windows, managing token budgets, and feeding agents the right information at the right time.",
              url: "https://machinelearningmastery.com/effective-context-engineering-for-ai-agents-a-developers-guide/",
            },
            {
              title: "How AI Agents Remember Things: Vector Stores in LLM Memory",
              source: "freeCodeCamp",
              tag: "Memory",
              desc: "Explains how agents persist information across sessions using vector databases — the technical foundation behind AI that actually remembers.",
              url: "https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/how-ai-agents-remember-things-vector-stores-in-llm-memory/",
            },
            {
              title: "How to Compress Your Prompts and Reduce LLM Costs",
              source: "freeCodeCamp",
              tag: "Cost Optimisation",
              desc: "Practical techniques for trimming prompt tokens without losing quality — useful once you're running prompts at any scale.",
              url: "https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/how-to-compress-your-prompts-and-reduce-llm-costs/",
            },
            {
              title: "Functional Personas: A Lean, Practical AI Workflow",
              source: "Smashing Magazine",
              tag: "Personas",
              desc: "How to build reusable AI personas that encode role, tone, and constraints — making your prompts consistent and portable across tools.",
              url: "https://www.smashingmagazine.com/2025/09/functional-personas-ai-lean-practical-workflow/",
            },
            {
              title: "How to Keep LLM Outputs Predictable Using Pydantic Validation",
              source: "freeCodeCamp",
              tag: "Output Reliability",
              desc: "Schema-based validation to enforce structured outputs from language models — essential reading if you're piping AI output into code.",
              url: "https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/how-to-keep-llm-outputs-predictable-using-pydantic-validation/",
            },
            {
              title: "How Do AI Agents Work?",
              source: "freeCodeCamp",
              tag: "AI Agents",
              desc: "A clear walkthrough of the perceive-reason-act loop that powers every AI agent, with a real-world email automation example using the OpenAI API.",
              url: "https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/how-do-ai-agents-work/",
            },
            {
              title: "The Best AI Models for Coding: Accuracy, Integration & Developer Fit",
              source: "JetBrains",
              tag: "Coding",
              desc: "JetBrains' breakdown of which AI models perform best for real development tasks — comparing accuracy, IDE integration depth, and fit for different developer workflows.",
              url: "https://blog.jetbrains.com/ai/2026/02/the-best-ai-models-for-coding-accuracy-integration-and-developer-fit/",
            },
            {
              title: "Claude Code Ultimate Guide",
              source: "GitHub / Florian Bruniaux",
              tag: "Developer Tools",
              desc: "The best community-built resource for Claude Code — 181 templates, 271-question quiz, agentic workflow patterns, hooks, plugins, and a security threat database.",
              url: "https://github.com/FlorianBruniaux/claude-code-ultimate-guide",
            },
            {
              title: "Effective Context Engineering",
              source: "Anthropic Engineering",
              tag: "Context Engineering",
              desc: "Anthropic's own engineering guide to context — how to structure what you give a model, when to compress, and why context quality is the highest-leverage variable in agent performance.",
              url: "https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/effective-context-engineering",
            },
            {
              title: "Agent Memory & Context Lifecycle",
              source: "Anthropic Cookbook",
              tag: "Memory",
              desc: "How agents manage what they remember across a session — in-context storage, external memory, summarisation strategies, and when each approach breaks down.",
              url: "https://github.com/anthropics/anthropic-cookbook/blob/main/tool_use/tool_use_agent.ipynb",
            },
            {
              title: "The 7 Types of Agent Memory: A Technical Guide for AI Engineers",
              source: "MarkTechPost",
              tag: "Memory",
              desc: "A technical guide breaking down the seven types of agent memory—working, semantic, episodic, procedural, retrieval, parametric, and prospective—and when to build each.",
              url: "https://www.marktechpost.com/2026/06/21/the-7-types-of-agent-memory-a-technical-guide-for-ai-engineers/",
            },
          ].map(r => (
            <a href={r.url} target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="reading-card">
              <div class="reading-meta">
                <span class="reading-tag">{r.tag}</span>
                <span class="reading-source">{r.source}</span>
              </div>
              <h3 class="reading-title">{r.title}</h3>
              <p class="reading-desc">{r.desc}</p>
              <span class="reading-cta">Read article →</span>
            </a>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>

    <aside class="prep-sidebar">
      <div class="sidebar-card">
        <h3>🥫 Ready-made context</h3>
        <p>The Pantry has pre-written role frames, context setters, and constraints you can drop straight into any prompt.</p>
        <a href="/pantry/" class="sidebar-link">Visit The Pantry →</a>
      </div>
      <div class="sidebar-card">
        <h3>🌶️ Build your own</h3>
        <p>The Spice Rack lets you mix context ingredients into a custom prompt.</p>
        <a href="/spice-rack/" class="sidebar-link">Open Spice Rack →</a>
      </div>
      <div class="sidebar-card">
        <h3>📖 See it in action</h3>
        <p>The Recipe Book has 26 prompts that put these principles into practice.</p>
        <a href="/prompts/" class="sidebar-link">Browse recipes →</a>
      </div>
      <div class="sidebar-card sidebar-chain">
        <h3>⛓️ Prompt chaining</h3>
        <p>Breaking complex tasks into 5 sequential micro-prompts boosts output quality by up to 67%.</p>
        <a href="#prompt-chaining" class="sidebar-link">Read the technique ↓</a>
      </div>
      <div class="sidebar-card sidebar-reading">
        <h3>📚 Further reading</h3>
        <p>Five technical deep-dives on context engineering, memory, cost, personas, and output validation.</p>
        <a href="#further-reading" class="sidebar-link">Jump to reading list ↓</a>
      </div>
    </aside>
  </div>
</Page>

<style>
.page-hero { padding: var(--s12) 0 var(--s8); max-width: var(--container-narrow); }
.page-hero h1 { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: clamp(2rem,5vw,3rem); margin: 0 0 var(--s3); }
.page-hero p { color: var(--text-2); font-size: 1.05rem; margin: 0; max-width: 560px; }

.prep-layout { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 260px; gap: var(--s8); padding-bottom: var(--s20); align-items: start; }

.prep-content { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--s12); }

.prep-section h2 { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1.5rem; margin: 0 0 var(--s5); }
.prep-section p { color: var(--text-2); line-height: 1.7; margin: 0 0 var(--s4); }
.prep-section p:last-child { margin: 0; }
.prep-section a { color: var(--accent); font-weight: 600; }

.ingredients-grid { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--s4); }
.ingredient-card { display: flex; gap: var(--s4); padding: var(--s4) var(--s5); background: var(--surface); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--r3); align-items: flex-start; }
.ingredient-icon { font-size: 1.5rem; flex-shrink: 0; line-height: 1; }
.ingredient-card h3 { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1rem; margin: 0 0 var(--s2); }
.ingredient-card p { font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--text-2); margin: 0; line-height: 1.6; }

.compare-table { border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--r3); overflow: hidden; }
.compare-row { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
.compare-header { background: var(--bg-alt); font-size: 0.8rem; font-weight: 700; }
.compare-header > div { padding: var(--s3) var(--s4); color: var(--text-3); }
.compare-row:not(.compare-header) { border-top: 1px solid var(--border-light); }
.compare-bad, .compare-good { padding: var(--s4); font-size: 0.875rem; line-height: 1.6; }
.compare-bad { background: var(--bg); border-right: 1px solid var(--border-light); }
.compare-good { background: var(--surface); }
.compare-quote { color: var(--text-2); font-style: italic; }

.tip-block { background: var(--accent-light); border: 1px solid var(--accent-border); border-radius: var(--r3); padding: var(--s5); margin: var(--s4) 0; }
.tip-block p { color: var(--text-2); font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0 0 var(--s2); }
.tip-block p:last-child { margin: 0; }

.checklist { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: var(--s4) 0; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--s3); }
.checklist li { display: flex; gap: var(--s3); font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-2); }
.checklist li::before { content: '□'; color: var(--accent); font-size: 1rem; flex-shrink: 0; }

.prep-sidebar { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--s4); position: sticky; top: calc(var(--nav-h) + var(--s4)); }
.sidebar-card { background: var(--surface); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--r3); padding: var(--s5); }
.sidebar-card h3 { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1rem; margin: 0 0 var(--s2); }
.sidebar-card p { font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--text-2); margin: 0 0 var(--s3); line-height: 1.5; }
.sidebar-link { font-size: 0.875rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--accent); text-decoration: none; }
.sidebar-link:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

/* ── Follow-up prompts grid ── */
.followup-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(220px, 1fr)); gap: var(--s3); margin: var(--s4) 0 var(--s5); }
.followup-card { background: var(--surface); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--r3); padding: var(--s3) var(--s4); display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--s2); }
.followup-label { font-size: 0.65rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.07em; color: var(--text-3); }
.followup-prompt { font-size: 0.82rem; font-family: var(--font-mono); color: var(--accent); line-height: 1.4; }
/* ── Prompt chaining section ── */
.section-kicker { font-size: 1rem; color: var(--text-2); font-style: italic; margin-bottom: var(--s6) !important; }
.chain-callout { display: flex; gap: var(--s5); align-items: center; background: var(--accent-light); border: 1px solid var(--accent-border); border-radius: var(--r3); padding: var(--s5) var(--s6); margin: var(--s5) 0 var(--s6); }
.chain-stat { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 3rem; font-weight: 900; color: var(--accent); line-height: 1; flex-shrink: 0; }
.chain-callout p { font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-2); margin: 0; line-height: 1.6; }
.chain-list { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: var(--s3) 0 var(--s6); display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--s3); }
.chain-list li { font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-2); line-height: 1.6; padding-left: var(--s5); position: relative; }
.chain-list li::before { content: '—'; position: absolute; left: 0; color: var(--accent); font-weight: 700; }
.chain-steps { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0; margin: var(--s4) 0 var(--s6); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--r3); overflow: hidden; }
.chain-step { display: flex; gap: var(--s4); align-items: flex-start; padding: var(--s4) var(--s5); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); background: var(--surface); }
.chain-step:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
.chain-step:hover { background: var(--bg-alt); }
.step-num { width: 28px; height: 28px; border-radius: 50%; background: var(--accent); color: #fff; font-size: 0.78rem; font-weight: 800; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; flex-shrink: 0; margin-top: 2px; }
.chain-step strong { font-size: 0.9rem; display: block; margin-bottom: var(--s1); }
.chain-step p { font-size: 0.82rem; color: var(--text-2); margin: 0; line-height: 1.5; }
.chain-compare .compare-bad p.compare-note, .chain-compare .compare-good p.compare-note { font-size: 0.78rem; color: var(--text-3); font-style: italic; margin: var(--s3) 0 0; padding-top: var(--s3); border-top: 1px solid var(--border-light); }
.chain-step-label { display: block; font-size: 0.65rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.07em; color: var(--accent); margin: var(--s4) 0 var(--s2); }
.chain-step-label:first-child { margin-top: 0; }
.chain-source { margin-top: var(--s5); padding: var(--s4) var(--s5); background: var(--bg-alt); border-radius: var(--r2); border: 1px solid var(--border-light); }
.chain-source p { font-size: 0.78rem; color: var(--text-3); margin: 0; }
.chain-source a { color: var(--accent); font-weight: 600; }
.prep-section h3 { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--s6) 0 var(--s4); color: var(--text); }
.sidebar-chain { border-color: var(--accent-border); }
/* ── Reading list ── */
.reading-list { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--s4); margin-top: var(--s5); }
.reading-card { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--s2); background: var(--surface); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--r3); padding: var(--s5); text-decoration: none; transition: border-color var(--t-fast), box-shadow var(--t-fast); }
.reading-card:hover { border-color: var(--accent); box-shadow: 0 2px 12px var(--shadow); }
.reading-meta { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--s3); }
.reading-tag { font-size: 0.65rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.07em; padding: 2px 8px; border-radius: var(--r-full); background: var(--accent-light); color: var(--accent); border: 1px solid var(--accent-border); }
.reading-source { font-size: 0.72rem; color: var(--text-3); font-weight: 600; }
